Feb 19 2005	Deceiving at best	We stayed at this hotel for 5 nights in Nov. 2003. I saw their ads on expedia and also checked for reviews and other postings. Nothing looked too bad, and I wasn't expecting much for the price. It was my daughter, age 14 and myself and we were visiting another daughter who was studying abroad in London and the location was perfect. From the outside it looks pretty good. I had a really hard time at check-in because no one spoke English well, but finally did confirm that we had a room and that I had paid in advance. Our room was out back in what looked like a garage that had been converted into rooms. We had to walk outside to get to our room (through the garden). It was so tiny and very dirty and smelled really moldy. Unfortunately I had paid in advance for the week, and I knew that arguing with the non-English speaking staff was liable to get me no satisfaction, so we decided to make the best of it. On the plus side, our room was extremely warm and being November and rainy in London, that was a welcome at the end of long day. Our water pressure was excellent, we never ran out of hot water, and we take really long showers. The breakfast was the same everyday, boiled egg, cornflakes, toast and coffee. We grew to like it, and that combined with tons of walking that we did everyday helped me to lose about 5 pounds on that trip. One wierd note, I had requested a taxi to take us to the airport on our last day. We had come in on the tube, but we were tired, and I had a few pounds left over so decided to treat ourselves to a comfortable ride out to the airport. Well it was like no taxi I had ever seen before, I think it was a relative of someone who worked at the hotel, maybe their private car. It was nice, and really clean, but obviously not a licensed taxi by any means. I was a little apprehensive about getting in the car with my kid and just hoping that the guy was not some serial killer or something, but he just took us to the airport. Never spoke a single word the whole was, and the radio was playing some Egyptian type music. My suggestion for the Hotel Oliver is don't stay there if the hotel experience is something you are looking forward to, but if you just want to crash, then it isn't too bad. Our rooms were very quiet and warm. And we just overlooked the dingy and dirty. We pretended we were camping, and made it into an adventure.	
