Mar 27 2004	A decent budget hotel.	This hotel is just like the ones that Americans are warned about in the travel books. It is not what you are accustomed to by American standards. The rooms are small and none-too-modern. It's just generally an old-fashioned place. That being said. I would certainly go back there again. It's cheap (we paid about $110 per double room in March 2004) and has a great central location. The breakfast consists of boiled eggs, corn flakes and toast, but is well presented. I've gotten less at more expensive London hotels.You hotel is not posh and you will not wish to hang around your room, but you'll be out seeing the sites. The staff is competent and helpful and the clientel was fine, mostly younger folks and Europeans. I stayed three nights and was never disturbed by unruly behavior. One hint, you will likely arrive via Earl's Court tube station, which is the closest station. The route from the station to the hotel is a little dreary. Keep in mind that the area just north of the hotel is much nicer and you can walk to Kennsington High Street in less than 10 minutes.In closing, the initial impression of the Hotel Oliver can be a little disconcerting to Americans used to American style motels. But the place is fine if all you are looking for is a place to rest after a long day of site seeing and theater. Save your money on the hotel bill and spend it elsewhere.	
